The legal record itself was then thinned. The Justice Department removed its public database of January 6 cases, eliminating a centralized record of charges, pleas, and sentences tied to the attack on Congress. In parallel, prosecutors closed cases against Trump\'92s co\uc0\u8209 defendants in the classified documents probe, cutting off a potential source of testimony and detail about how sensitive materials had been handled. Combined with the pardons, these steps did not just alter outcomes; they obscured them. Citizens, journalists, and historians were left with fewer tools to reconstruct what had happened and how the state had responded. That loss was by design.\
\
Taken together, these moves turned law from a check into a shield. Pro\uc0\u8209 regime violence and allied misconduct were not only forgiven; they were lifted out of the ordinary channels of accountability and memory. Those who had enforced the law in the prior term were removed. Those who had broken it in service of the president were restored. The message was plain without needing to be spoken: the risk of crossing the regime now lay in investigating it, not in attacking its opponents. Law still spoke in legal terms, but its direction had flipped.\
